Cutthroat trout caught and released on the Greybull River in Wyoming.  The Greybull has the most pristine and intact cutthroat population in the US due to some irrigation diversions that prevented brown, rainbow and brook trout from moving into their habitat.  The entire upper watershed is protected by the Pitchfork Ranch owners who prohibit almost any fishing.  We were lucky enough to get a chance to fish it while we were doing some restoration to one of the side creeks 2 years ago.  The area also is home to over 8,000 elk, grizzlies and a large wolf population.

description:
This is the fish that shut down Atascadero Creek in 2013.  You can't see it in the photo, but it's hovering over its nest. 

Lisa Thompson (UC Davis) told me this about the sacred fish:

Rainbow trout and steelhead (trout) are the same species, Oncorhynchus mykiss.   The only difference is that steelhead migrate to the ocean, where food is generally more abundant, so when they return to freshwater to spawn they are larger than the "resident" rainbow trout who spend their whole life in freshwater.  The trade-off for the steelhead is that they have to brave the more dangerous ocean conditions, with larger predators, in order to gain the size and reproductive advantage.  The larger the female, the more eggs she produces.

Interestingly, steelhead mothers can produce rainbow trout offspring, and vice versa.  In southern California, where long droughts have occurred historically, this flexibility in life history probably helped the trout to survive.  If the creeks didn't flow enough to break through the lagoon sandbars for many years in a row, any steelhead out in the ocean would have died without reproducing, but the population could have been maintained by the resident rainbow trout in the creek headwaters (e.g., Rattlesnake Creek up above Mission Creek - the first place I saw southern steelhead trout). Once a good rain finally arrived, some of the rainbow trout offspring would have converted to being steelhead, migrated to the ocean, and returned to freshwater large and able to rapidly increase the population size.

In California the steelhead between Santa Cruz and Santa Maria are listed as threatened under the federal ESA, and between Santa Maria and the Mexico border they are listed as endangered.  There are steelhead as far south in California as Camp Pendleton, near Oceanside, and I've seen rainbow trout in the Tijuana River east of San Diego.  There are also a few isolated populations of trout in the highlands of Baja California, and east of the Gulf of California in Mexico.

description: a small fry approx 3 in. long.

The brook trout's body is elongate with an average length of 38.1-50.8 cm, is only slightly laterally compressed; the body has its greatest depth at or in front of the origin of the dorsal fin. Another physical characteristic of the brook trout is an adipose fin and a caudal fin that is slightly forked. The coloration of the brook trout is very distinct and can be spectacular. The back of the brook trout is dark olive-green to dark brown, sometimes almost black, the sides are lighter and become silvery white ventrally. On the back and top of the head there are wormy cream colored wavy lines known as vermiculations which break up into spots on the side. In addition to the pale spots on the side there are smaller more discrete red spots with bluish halos. The fins of the brook trout are also distinct; the dorsal fin has heavy black wavy lines, the caudal fin has black lines, the anal, pelvic and pectoral fins have white edges followed by black and then reddish coloration.

description: Fish keep spawning/hatching in the portion of Hobson Creek that dries up year after year. Last year we saw the fish jumping and spawning and they were definitely salmonoids. This year, we only saw babies. This one recently died in a pool that formed after the year's one major storm shifted all the pools and gravel areas. We've seen other fish trying to make it in their little dwindling pools, but this one was quite large for the size of the pool it was in. No dark speckles on body, faintly pink line on its side. Mouth all white inside.
Caught by John Rhoades

description:
Trucha del Río Yaqui o aparique capturado en un proyecto acuícola comunitario dentro del APFF Campo Verde, Chihuahua, con el que se pretende evaluar la viabilidad comercial de la especie en substitución de la trucha arcoiris y medir su éxito reproductivo para ser liberadas en arroyos y ríos donde ya ha desaparecido por sobre explotación o contaminación.
Las truchas nativas mexicanas (Oncorhynchus sp.)han estado sujetas a una serie de estudios biogeográficos y genéticos para determinar cuantas especies se encuentran en los ríos y arroyos de la vertiente del Pacífico y se determinó que se trata de al menos 5 linajes independientes los cuales aguardan su descripción para elevarlos a categoría de especie o subespecie.

The animal that was observed for this assignment was the Chinook Salmon, which was photographed at Bronte Creek National Park in Oakville, Ontario. The scientific name of the Chinook Salmon is Oncorhynchus tshawytscha, and has many common names including: King, Blackmouth, Quinnat, and Chub (Fisheries and Oceans Canada, 2013). 
	The Chinook Salmon has many different habitats. They start off in freshwater when they are born, migrate into the ocean as they are developing, and return as mature salmon to the rivers and streams where they were born to mate and reproduce (Scott, 2003). The freshwater streams are cold – around 14 degrees Celsius – and have fast flowing currents. These rivers are deep with coarse gravel found at the bottom (Scott, 2003). These salmon can also be found in estuaries, which provide the perfect transition zone from freshwater to salt water for developing salmon, in addition to being a great source of food and shelter (Scott, 2003). In the oceans, Chinook Salmon either stay close to shore, or migrate thousands of miles into the deep waters of the Pacific Ocean (Scott, 2003). The geographic range of these fish varies greatly. They are natively found in the Pacific Ocean. Their ranges span from Monterey Bay, California to the Chukchi Sea in Alaska, and from the Anadyr River in Siberia to Hokkaido, Japan (Scott, 2003). In addition to being found in these locations, they have also been introduced to numerous bodies of water around the world like those in New Zealand and the Great Lakes as a non-native species (Scott, 2003).  
	The Chinook Salmon is the largest of all the Pacific salmon species (Scott, 2003). The average weight of a Chinook Salmon is about 30 pounds (Scott, 2003).  Their average length is about 36 inches, growing a maximum of 58 inches long (Scott, 2003).  The lifespan of a Chinook Salmon is variable, with some salmon dying within their first year and others living 8 years or more (Scott, 2003).  The average age of mature adults is around 4-6 years in the wild (Scott, 2003). However, the average age of Chinook Salmon tend to depend on the location of their habitats. Those salmon that are situated more south have an average lifespan of about 2-4 years, while those salmon that have their habitats up north have average lifespans of about 5-7 years (Scott, 2003). Human impacts to the environment and habitats of the Chinook Salmon, like decreased water flow, increased siltation, and a decrease in oxygen availability, has played a role on their lifespan (Scott, 2003). The mortality rate of eggs and young salmon has increased due to these implications (Scott, 2003).  
	The diets of the Chinook Salmon vary depending on the age of the fish. Younger Chinook Salmon, 1 or 2 year olds, tend to eat the larvae and very young fish, as well as krill, crab and other micronekton in freshwater (Thayer, Field, & Sydeman, 2014). In ocean waters, the prey of the adult Chinook Salmon is different. They tend to feed on krill, crab, anchovies, herring, and squid, depending on which food is more abundant (Thayer, Field, & Sydeman, 2014). Also, we see Chinook Salmon feeding on Alewife, which is an overly abundant species of herring in the Great Lakes (Jacobs, Madenjian, Bunnell, Warner, & Claramunt, 2013). These salmon were brought into this area to control the booming population of Alewife (Jacobs, Madenjian, Bunnell, Warner, & Claramunt, 2013).
	During mating season, which is once a year, adult Chinook Salmon return to their birth streams (Scott, 2003).  The time of the year for breeding depends on the population of salmon, as well as the river; on average, Chinook Salmon tend to breed during the summer and autumn (Chinook Salmon, n.d). Sexual maturity is reached from ages 2-7, and soon after mating, they die (Scott, 2003). Reproduction occurs first with the female using her tail to dig a redds in the gravel of the river, which is the spawning nest for their eggs (Scott, 2003). The female deposits about 3,000-14,000 eggs, then the males deposit their sperm, and both parents guard the eggs until they die (Scott, 2003). The times at which the Chinook Salmon mate differ, like during the summer or autumn, but the younglings tend to hatch around the same time during the spring, where the vegetation is blossoming (Scott, 2003). In order for fertilization to occur, certain communication rituals must be completed by both the male and female Chinook Salmon (Berejikian, Tezak, & LaRae, 2000). While the females are busy building the redd for their eggs, the males are participating in a series of crosses and vibrations near the females (Berejikian, Tezak, & LaRae, 2000). Once the females are finished, they partake in intersexual selection – choosing their mate. Females tend to be more likely to choose the larger males that vibrate more than the males that are smaller and vibrate less (Berejikian, Tezak, & LaRae, 2000). Once the male is chosen, the female will go close to the male, and vibrate quickly to induce sperm release from the male (Berejikian, Tezak, & LaRae, 2000).	
	The Chinook Salmon have many predators, but they vary depending on whether these fish are young or adults. Young salmon have a higher mortality rate due to high predation because of their small size (Scott, 2003). Predators like striped bass, American shad, sculpins, and sea gulls like to feed on these small fish (Scott, 2003). When adult salmon return to their native rivers they are targeted by larger predators (Scott, 2003). Common predators include bears, killer whales, sea lions, seals, otters, and eagles (Scott, 2003). In coastal waters, killer whales are the top predators of these large salmon (Fisheries and Oceans Canada, 2013).
	Over the years, the population of the Chinook Salmon has been declining due to overfishing, climate change, damming, diverting water and habitat destruction (Scott, 2003). Damming blocks the salmon from returning to their birthplace, diverting water away from streams causes the river temperature to rise reducing the oxygen capacity, and habitat destruction takes away shelter for young salmon to use as protection from predators (Scott, 2003). The results of human actions are affecting this species of salmon, and are what is causing them to become endangered (Scott, 2003).
	Did you know that the world record for the heaviest Chinook Salmon is 127 pounds (Fisheries and Oceans Canada, 2013)?
